comment:
I've removed US Navy veteran from my profile.  11 years I gave my full measure, met so many amazing people, learned so many things, so many profound experiences. I've removed  US Navy veteran from my profile. Let that sink in for a moment. 

It's something that's been weighing on me for quite a while tbh. Disillusionment is a bitter-sweet affair. My heart is full knowing I *finally have eyes to see*, but my heart is sad with the realization I could have believed in a deceitful caricature with so much dedication & pride. 

It is a huge loss for me.The Navy has always been such a large part of my identity; I grew up there. But I can no longer in good conscious wear this government as a badge of honor. She's betrayed us all in my opinion.

I'll always be grateful for the start to life the Navy gave me. I'll always be proud of my work as a professional. I'll always be fond of the officers placed above me (squadron level) & strongly connected to the men & women that served with me.

But I'm done being proud of having served a caricature. America is not what I grew up thinking it was. It shreds me to say it. I make marked distinction between America the government and America the people. But that's true of every nation.

If ever we return to our founding principles, I will consider a tall flag pole in my yard with a blue eagle & anchor bearing Navy banner right beneath Old Glory. Until that day, I'll fly neither.

comment:
Don't fall for it. I joined in 2018 and I suffered from starvation, lack of healthcare, and no bathroom breaks. It was made clear to us on a constant basis that we weren't wanted or needed while there was a 6,000 troop shortage. When I went to prison school (aka AIT) I was screwed out of my certifications and then when I got to my unit I was told I wasn't allowed to do my job. Was bullied, turned into a slave, and had all opportunities taken from me until I went to BH and was kicked out for "adjustment disorder" by extremely unprofessional and abusive therapists who only saw me for one month. I now suffer from severe PTSD. I have to relive the nightmare everyday because I never once got the opportunity  to "be all I can be." The Army really isn't like what they're portraying in the commercial. 99% of your time will be spent doing worthless details, and there is strong chance you will never get to do your job. The Army has been mismanaged into the ground and will provide you with no benefits whatsoever.

Only the Coast Guard and Airforce are worth it. Go where you're wanted, not where you're hated.

comment: @Rikoe A I am making a public apology. I fight daily to fix soldiers paperwork so they can get the services they need so families and soldiers have a place they can call home for at least the three years they are here.    You are also quickly to call out a person whom you think is a toxic leader just like I didn't listen to your full story.  I fight for my soldiers and still am fighting the good fight.  I take it day by day, sometimes minute by minute.  It was not until all the medical personnel I saw and they could find absolutely no physical reason for my aches and pains, sleeping through several alarm clocks, snapping at my leadership.  I knew something was wrong.  Sometimes the good, the bad, and really ugly stressors of life can cause the physical ailments.  I was lucky to retire with 90% from the VA and no retirement from the Army.  I spent a good 19 years and three months in and was always told I am too soft spoken and I would have a hard time with my Soldiers.   Never once had I raised my voice or made a soldier feel like their issues  are trivial.  I took care of them,  I am sorry that your leadership was so cruel.  Feb 94- May 13.

comment:
@Ken Penders This is why it's so important to listen to soldiers' stories and not just call them liars or harrass them. Since I have severe PTSD due to toxic leadership and therapist abuse I can't trust therapists anymore (I've tried several times). So retelling my story is a form of therapy for me. During the period of time in which I was being driven to suicide by everyone around me, I had nobody to talk to, and my therapists were making everything worse. I was victim blamed, gaslighted, and even told that I shouldn't be in the Army within the first five minutes of the first conversation. I wish I had walked out that day. I still regret not  committing suicide as well because now I have to relive the trauma everyday.

I'm glad that soldiers are waking up and telling their children and other individuals not to join. They're doing gods work - so many people leave the Army suffering from all types of trauma, either mental or physical, and it takes a huge toll. The Army definitely set me up for failure from the start and I just wish I had access to the support structure necessary to help me succeed.

comment:
‚Äã@Ann Marie Marczak No, I actually knew going in I was going to be yelled at. It didn't bother me at all. What I didn't expect is that the Army hated new recruits THIS much, and at such an extreme level. I suffered from starvation during in-processing to the point where people were vomiting up water due to empty stomachs and I had to fight passing out every morning while standing in line. People literally peed on themselves because it was the summer, and no bathroom breaks were ever scheduled. One girl had to stay behind because her knees became infected and they wouldn't let her receive medical care. We weren't even in basic training yet, just doing admin stuff, so why are we being treated this horribly? Basic was much easier in comparison and actually treated us way better than this.

During basic I had extremely bad bronchitis. It was so severe that I was having constant coughing attacks and vomiting. I was losing weight rapidly. I wasn't allowed to receive medical care until my last phase, and even then I was given just weak cough medicine that did nothing for me. The only reason I was able to pass every PT test was because before I joined the Army I had practiced heat and pain tolerance. I ran everyday. I was more prepared than most of the other soldiers there. If I hadn't I probably would've died. It was so bad that when I did finally get proper healthcare in AIT I found out I had rib fractures from all of the coughing. I had joined the Army to learn a skilled trade, but I also wanted to see the world and also deploy to a war zone at least once. I didn't mind dying for my country. I didn't even care about this "industrial war complex" that soldiers sometimes complain about. I just wanted to feel like I was contributing to something and gain experience for a job when I got out.

I had no idea that my sponsor was going to be an extremely toxic corporal who had been demoted, who spent every day talking down to me and stressing me out. I had no idea I was going to have to be transported by civilian police onto base because nobody came to pick us up in the middle of the night when we landed at the train station at our first duty station. I had no idea I was going to be screwed out of my MOS certifications because I was put in night school. I had no idea that I was being assigned to a nondeployable unit. I had no idea that the Chief would rule the shop with an iron fist and hand pick people to do machining, which was a passion of mine and part of my job. I had no idea that I would become a slave to worthless details as a result due to severe talent mismanagement. I had no idea I was going to be bullied right in front of the NCOs, and have opportunities like hazmat school taken away from me at the last minute.

I had no idea that Behavioral Health was never an option. When I went inpatient after the abuse from my unit and my therapist had driven me to my breaking point, I had no idea every single person there was going to be misdiagnosed as having adjustment disorder and then chaptered out of the Army. I thought the Army had grown past that in 2021, but apparently not. 

Despite all of the abuse, the trauma, and the pain I knew that there were still hope out there. I wanted to renlist in a new MOS, work on my mental health, and try to get back what was stolen from me but all that went down the drain when I went to BH. Since then I've been diagnosed with PTSD and have a 100% P&T rating for it.

You are not a mentor, nor a coach, and I can tell the type of toxic person you were in the Army. What you wrote was incredibly insulting and narcassistic. The Army clearly wasn't for you, and its sad that you got as far as you did, to the point where you became an NCO. Please don't be the type of person you were in service. Leave that toxic BS behind and learn put yourself in other's shoes, not talk down to them because you have no idea the amount of unnecessary trauma I went through. As a fellow female, please learn to have compassion for others.
author: Rikoe A
